# Overview

This project demonstrates deploying multiple EC2 instances behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with proper network isolation, health checks, and security group design. The ALB acts as the single public entry point, while EC2 instances remain private and inaccessible directly from the internet.

⸻

# What I Built
	•	Two EC2 instances running a simple Apache web server
	•	Instances deployed across different Availability Zones for redundancy
	•	An Application Load Balancer spanning two public subnets
	•	A target group with health checks on /
	•	Security groups enforcing ALB-only access to EC2 instances
	•	NAT Gateway to allow private instances outbound internet access

⸻

# Key Implementation Details
	•	User Data was used to automatically install and start Apache on each EC2 instance, with each instance serving slightly different content to verify load balancing.
	•	The ALB listens on HTTP (port 80) and forwards traffic to a target group containing both EC2 instances.
	•	Health checks were configured on the root path (/) to ensure only healthy instances receive traffic.
	•	Security groups were isolated properly:
	•	ALB security group allows HTTP from anywhere.
	•	EC2 security group allows HTTP only from the ALB security group.
	•	EC2 instances have no public IP addresses.
	•	EC2 instances were placed in private subnets, with outbound internet access provided via a NAT Gateway to allow package installation during boot.

⸻

# Debugging & Lessons Learned
	•	Initial health check failures (502 Bad Gateway) revealed a connectivity issue, not an application issue.
	•	Monitoring data showed requests reaching the ALB but not the instances.
	•	The root cause was that EC2 instances in private subnets could not reach the internet to install packages via user data.
	•	This was resolved by introducing a NAT Gateway and a private route table, reinforcing concepts from Assignment 1.
	•	Once networking was corrected, health checks passed and traffic successfully alternated between instances.

⸻

# Verification
	•	Visiting the ALB DNS name successfully returns responses from both EC2 instances.
	•	Refreshing the page alternates content, confirming load balancing.
	•	Target group health checks report both instances as healthy.

⸻

# Outcome

This assignment reinforced core DevOps concepts:
	•	Separation of public and private resources
	•	Load balancer–centric architectures
	•	Security group referencing for least privilege
	•	The dependency between networking design and application behavior

